For that we will need to apply very strict accounting rules.</p><u><b><span size="2">1. Start Date: August 1, 2024</span></b></u><u><b><span size="2">2. Total Investment = $20,000.00</span></b></u><u><b><span size="2">3. Trading account Starting Balance/Equity= $6,346.90</span></b></u><u><b><span size="2">4. Business Account Starting Balance = $20,000.00 -$6,346.90 = $13,653.10 </span></b></u> <p><span size="2">(Safe money used to cover for expenses including Monthly Return.)</span></p><u><b><span size="2">5. Monthly Return on Investment = 10%TI = $2,000.00</span></b></u><p> 
The "Official" statement that the government considers is Quarterly (3 months).<br>
So we will use it as a reference.<br>
Because Start Date is August 1st, we will use the Monthly Statement for August and September and Q4 statement thereafter...</p><u><b><span size="3">We will declare this business a failure the day we run out of resources.</span></b></u> </div> <div id="edit14956949"> <u><b><span size="3">Rules of Engagement</span></b></u><u><b><span size="3">Rule One</span></b></u><br> <u><b><span size="3">No Soldier can enter the Battlefield before being fully financed.</span></b></u> <p><span size="2">We do not use leverage and only trade what we can afford. </span><br> <span size="2">A Soldier has two (02) costs:</span><br> <span size="2">The first one is what an accountant will call Cost Of Goods which is the drawdown a Soldier can create, a capped value in our strategy.</span><br> <span size="2">The second cost is the cost to hold the position itself. </span></p><p><span size="2"><u><b>Very important note:</b></u> </span><br> <span size="2">One has to be very careful with this last part because there is no standard policy common to all brokers. Some do not withhold margin for fully hedged positions but most of the brokers I know do withhold an important amount for each side of the hedge.</span></p><p> 
